      <hedline>
        <hl1>Disability Redefined</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from William G Stothers, Center for an Accessible Society deputy director, says Charles Scwab can say he is dyslexic but insist that he is not disabled, but changing the words does not change the attitudes behind them (Aug 8 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Charles Schwab, the brokerage executive, is dyslexic, but insists he's not disabled (news article, Aug. 8).  Those of us with disabilities empathize, but we know that changing the words doesn't change the attitudes behind them.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Charles Schwab, the brokerage executive, is dyslexic, but insists he's not disabled (news article, Aug. 8).  Those of us with disabilities empathize, but we know that changing the words doesn't change the attitudes behind them.</p>
        <p>It is important, however, to support Mr. Schwab's idea that schools should see children as distinct learners in need of individualized attention. The same idea should be applied to adults. As a nearly lifelong wheelchair user and newspaper editor, I was different (perhaps), but not ''disabled'' in newsrooms. I would have been disabled had I tried to be a construction worker. Advancements in medicine and technology are hustling us into a new understanding of what it means to be disabled.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM G. STOTHERS  San Diego, Aug. 8, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is deputy director of the Center for an Accessible Society.</p>
      </block>
